<subSubSection pageId="3" pageNumber="586" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="3.[151,1436,152,1135]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,309,824,847]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Remarks.</emphasis>
The female of new species is distinguished from the similar 
<taxonomicName authority="Meade-Waldo, 1910" authorityName="Meade-Waldo" authorityYear="1910" box="[965,1401,823,847]" class="Insecta" family="Eumenidae" genus="Discoelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turneri">
<emphasis box="[965,1159,823,847]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Discoelius turneri</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Meade-Waldo" box="[1174,1395,824,847]" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" refString="Meade-Waldo, G. (1910) New species of Diploptera in the collection of the British Museum. Annals and Magazine of Natural History, 5, 30 - 51." type="journal article" year="1910">Meade-Waldo, 1910</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
by the combination of the following characters: clypeus with straight basal margin (emarginate in 
<taxonomicName box="[1161,1267,856,879]" class="Insecta" family="Eumenidae" genus="Discoelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turneri">
<emphasis box="[1161,1267,856,879]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">D. turneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); posterior face of propodeum strongly reticulate with a high median carina running whole length of propodeum from a short and nearly rounded propodeal fovea (
<figureCitation box="[440,506,920,943]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 11" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 11. Discoelius vasukii sp. nov., ♀, 5. Posterior portion of mesosoma; 6. Mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Posterior portion of propodeum; 8. Lower lateral portion of propodeum; 9. T 1, dorsal view; 10. T 2, dorsal view; 11. Posterior metasomal segments, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/801126/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 5</figureCitation>
) (posterior face of propodeum weakly reticulate and propodeal fovea elongate in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Eumenidae" genus="Discoelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turneri">
<emphasis box="[1410,1429,920,943]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[151,225,952,975]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">turneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); T1 with strong macropunctures, not finely punctate (
<figureCitation box="[813,878,952,975]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 11" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 11. Discoelius vasukii sp. nov., ♀, 5. Posterior portion of mesosoma; 6. Mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Posterior portion of propodeum; 8. Lower lateral portion of propodeum; 9. T 1, dorsal view; 10. T 2, dorsal view; 11. Posterior metasomal segments, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/801126/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 9</figureCitation>
); T2 with a narrow median apical lamella (
<figureCitation box="[1342,1422,952,975]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 11" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 11. Discoelius vasukii sp. nov., ♀, 5. Posterior portion of mesosoma; 6. Mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Posterior portion of propodeum; 8. Lower lateral portion of propodeum; 9. T 1, dorsal view; 10. T 2, dorsal view; 11. Posterior metasomal segments, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/801126/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 10</figureCitation>
), subsequent terga without apical lamellae (
<figureCitation box="[595,670,984,1007]" captionStart="FIGURES 5 – 11" captionStartId="2.[151,257,1798,1820]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,194,1777]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 5 – 11. Discoelius vasukii sp. nov., ♀, 5. Posterior portion of mesosoma; 6. Mesosoma, lateral view; 7. Posterior portion of propodeum; 8. Lower lateral portion of propodeum; 9. T 1, dorsal view; 10. T 2, dorsal view; 11. Posterior metasomal segments, dorsal view." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/801126/files/figure.png" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">Fig. 11</figureCitation>
) (T2–T3 with well developed apical lamella, and T4 with apical lamella only at lateral corners in 
<taxonomicName box="[422,529,1016,1039]" class="Insecta" family="Eumenidae" genus="Discoelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turneri">
<emphasis box="[422,441,1016,1039]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">D</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis box="[455,529,1016,1039]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">turneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
); two small round ferruginous spots on each side of pronotum absent (present in 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Eumenidae" genus="Discoelius" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="586" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="turneri">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="586">D. turneri</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
